@node Purpose
@chapter Purpose

This library provides MSVC symbol demangling functionality, currently
using the existing LLVM's MSVC demangler code.  It can be used by BFD,
GDB and binutils to demangle Microsoft Visual C++ symbols.

@node Licensing
@chapter Licensing

This library is licensed under Apache 2.0 with LLVM Exception.

@node API
@chapter API

The library exposes a C API compatible with libiberty's demangling
interface.

@section Core Demangling Functions

@deftypefun {char *} msvc_demangle (const char *@var{mangled}, int @var{options})
Demangle an MSVC symbol name.  Returns the demangled string, or
@code{NULL} if demangling fails.  Takes the same options as libiberty's
@code{cplus_demangle} for compatibility.  The caller must free the
returned string.
@end deftypefun

@section MSVC-Specific Utility Functions

@deftypefun {char *} llvm_msvc_class_name_from_physname (const char *@var{physname})
Extract the class name from an MSVC mangled physical name.
@end deftypefun

@deftypefun {char *} llvm_msvc_method_name_from_physname (const char *@var{physname})
Extract the method name from an MSVC mangled physical name.
@end deftypefun

@section BFD Integration Functions

@deftypefun {char *} bfd_demangle (bfd *@var{abfd}, const char *@var{mangled}, int @var{options})
Unified BFD demangling function.  Automatically detects symbol type
and uses the appropriate demangler.

@table @var
@item abfd
BFD object context.
@item mangled
The mangled symbol name.
@item options
Demangling options (@code{DMGL_*} flags).
@end table

Returns the demangled string (caller must free), or @code{NULL} if
demangling failed.  If an MSVC demangler has been registered via
@code{bfd_set_msvc_demangler} and the symbol looks like an MSVC mangled
name, the registered callback is used instead of @code{cplus_demangle}.
@end deftypefun

@deftypefun void bfd_set_msvc_demangler (char *(*@var{fn})(const char *, int))
Register a callback for MSVC symbol demangling.  Call once after
@code{bfd_init}.  Passing @code{NULL} disables MSVC demangling.
@end deftypefun

@node Integration
@chapter Integration

The library is built as a separate static library,
@code{libdemangle_msvc}, which is then linked into GDB and binutils.

@code{msvc_demangle} is invoked from within @code{bfd_demangle} by
checking the mangled name prefix and determining whether the symbol is
in MSVC format.  The MSVC demangler is registered once via
@code{bfd_set_msvc_demangler} after @code{bfd_init}, avoiding mandatory
linking of @code{libbfd} with @code{libdemangle_msvc}.  Only the tools
that require @code{libdemangle_msvc} register the callback.

@code{bfd_is_msvc_symbol} is an internal function that determines
whether a mangled name is in MSVC format.  A symbol is considered
MSVC-style if:

@itemize @bullet
@item
It starts with @samp{?}.
@item
It starts with a combination of @samp{.} and/or @samp{$} characters
followed by @samp{?} (follows the existing @code{bfd_demangle} behavior,
which strips these characters).
@item
It matches @samp{$ANYTHING$?}, which represents MSVC compiler-generated
prefixes.
@end itemize

The decision of whether a symbol is MSVC-style is kept inside BFD in
case future logic needs to examine the binary further (for example,
stripping additional prefixes or suffixes, or checking the target
triplet).

@section Architecture Overview

@example
@group
+-------------------+
|  Binutils Tool    |  (nm, addr2line, objdump, etc.)
|  or GDB           |
+--------+----------+
         |
         v
+-------------------+
| bfd_demangle      |  Detects symbol type (MSVC vs Itanium)
+--------+----------+
         |
    +----+------+
    v           v
+---------+  +----------------+
|libiberty|  |libdemangle_msvc|
|(Itanium)|  |(MSVC/LLVM)     |
+---------+  +----------------+
@end group
@end example

@section Symbol Format Detection

@code{bfd_is_msvc_symbol} identifies MSVC symbols by:

@itemize @bullet
@item
Symbol starts with @samp{?} (standard MSVC mangling).
@item
Symbol starts with combination of @samp{.} and @samp{$} ending with
@samp{?} (with prefix stripping).
@item
Symbol matches @samp{$ANYTHING$?} (compiler-generated prefixes).
@end itemize

The detection logic is kept in BFD to allow future enhancements like:

@itemize @bullet
@item
Examining the binary's target triplet.
@item
Additional prefix/suffix stripping based on binary format.
@item
Platform-specific symbol recognition.
@end itemize

@section Registration Architecture

To avoid mandatory linking of @code{libdemangle-msvc} into
@code{libbfd}, @code{msvc_demangle} is registered once via
@code{bfd_set_msvc_demangler}:

@itemize @bullet
@item
Tools that don't use MSVC demangling don't link
@code{libdemangle-msvc}.
@item
Tools that support MSVC demangling call
@code{bfd_set_msvc_demangler(msvc_demangle)} after @code{bfd_init()}.
@item
@code{bfd_demangle} calls the appropriate demangler based on symbol
format.
@end itemize

@section Binutils Tool Integration

Tools call @code{bfd_set_msvc_demangler(msvc_demangle)} after
@code{bfd_init()}.

@node Building
@chapter Building

@section Configure Options

Both GDB and binutils accept a @option{--with-msvc-demangler} flag:

@table @option
@item --with-msvc-demangler=auto
Default.  Enables MSVC demangling if a Windows target is detected
(i.e.@: @option{--enable-targets=all} or a @code{*-*-mingw*},
@code{*-*-cygwin*}, or @code{*-*-pe*} target).

@item --with-msvc-demangler=yes
Force enable MSVC demangling regardless of target.

@item --with-msvc-demangler=no
@itemx --without-msvc-demangler
Disable MSVC demangling even for Windows targets.
@end table

@section Standalone Build

@example
cd libdemangle-msvc
make clean
make
# Creates libdemangle-msvc.a
@end example

@section Debugging

Pass @option{--enable-msvc-demangle-debug} to @command{configure} to
enable diagnostic output from the msvc demangler's.

@example
./configure --enable-msvc-demangle-debug
@end example

@section ROCgdb Build

@example
./configure --enable-targets=all --with-msvc-demangler
make all-libdemangle-msvc
@end example

@node Testing
@chapter Testing

Run the test suite:

@example
cd libdemangle-msvc/testsuite
make check
@end example

